
1. What is a repository in GitHub?

	A GitHub repository (repo) stores all project files, code, documentation, and their complete revision history. It acts as the central hub for collaboration, version control, and issue tracking.

Structure example:


my-streamlit-app/
├── app.py              # Main application
├── requirements.txt    # Dependencies
├── README.md          # Documentation
└── .git/              # Hidden Git history folder



2. What is the purpose of a commit?

	Commits create version snapshots with descriptive messages, enabling rollback to any previous state:


git add app.py
git commit -m "Add bcrypt authentication + forgot password"

Benefits:

    Time travel: git checkout abc123 → Previous version

    Accountability: Who changed what, when

    Diff comparison: See exact line changes

    Branch point: Starting new features safely

Commit frequency: 3-5 per feature (atomic changes).



3. Why do developers use branches?

	Branches enable parallel development without breaking main code:


main ── A ── B (stable production)
       │
     feature/auth ── C ── D (experimentation)

Developer workflow:

git checkout -b feature/hr-dashboard
# Work → Commit → Test
git checkout main
git merge feature/hr-dashboard

Prevents: Developer A breaks login while Developer B builds dashboard.



4. What is the difference between push and pull?

| Action | Direction                          | Purpose                       |
| ------ | ---------------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Push   | Local → Remotegit push origin main | Upload your commits to GitHub |
| Pull   | Remote → Localgit pull origin main | Download latest team changes  |

Daily cycle:

Your laptop → git push (upload your work)
Team changes → git pull (sync teammates)

Conflicts resolved during pull → Git merge tool.



5. Why is README important in a project?

	README.md = Project front door read by 95% of visitors (recruiters, collaborators):


❌ Empty README → "Dead project?"
✅ Professional README → "Active developer!"

